<section xml:id="subsec-sines-and-cosines-of-complementary-angles" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Sines and Cosines of Complementary Angles</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.4 Trigonometry 1
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Relate sines and cosines of complementary angles
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <introduction component="lesson-plan">
            <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define complementary angles as two angles whose sum is <m>90^\circ</m>. State the co-function identities: <m>\sin(90^\circ - \theta) = \cos \theta</m> and <m>\cos(90^\circ - \theta) = \sin \theta</m>. Explain that <q>cosine</q> means <q>complement's sine</q>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Read sine and cosine values from tables for complementary angle pairs. Use the identity <m>\sin A = \cos B \Rightarrow A + B = 90^\circ</m> to find unknown angles. Solve equations involving complementary angle relationships.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems using complementary angle identities, such as finding heights and distances from given trigonometric values. Verify results using both sine/cosine tables and the complementary relationship.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/trigonometry-1/sines-and-cosines-of-complementary-angles.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/trigonometry-1/step-by-step-guide_sines-and-cosines-of-complementary-angles.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery / Engage</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Teacher's Role During Discovery:</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Circulate among pairs, ensuring students are reading sine and cosine tables correctly.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Ask guiding questions:</alert> <q>What do you notice about <m>40^\circ</m> and <m>50^\circ</m>? What is their sum?</q>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Encourage students to look for patterns across all four pairs.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Surface student thinking by asking pairs to share observations.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Bridge from discovery to formal definition of complementary angles.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        If you have an Internet connection, show Learners the interactive exploration.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

 
    
    <activity xml:id="auto_p7e7blt2">
        <p xml:id="auto_wk8raw4i">
            <m>\textbf{Work in pairs}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_crzuktwp">
            <term>What you require:</term> A pencil, a ruler, a scientific calculator (<m>\textbf{for verification}</m>), working material and a printed sine and cosine table.
        </p>
        <p>
            You can use <xref ref="trig-table"/> if needed.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_gnp8sj8r">
            <ol xml:id="auto_j351wei3">
                <li xml:id="auto_64vba4xp">
                    
                    <p xml:id="auto_icrcmhvo">
                        Read from the tables the values of the
                        following pairs of angles.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_34gfcrug">
                        <ol xml:id="auto_smji66el" marker="(a)">
                            <li xml:id="auto_0fp1a6m7">
                                <p xml:id="auto_4012cf42">
                                    <m>\sin\,40^\circ \quad \cos\,50^\circ</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_hmc31mui">
                                <p xml:id="auto_ygdt94ov">
                                    <m>\cos\,30^\circ \quad \sin\,60^\circ</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_1rukom9j">
                                <p xml:id="auto_12lm4c64">
                                    <m>\sin\,70^\circ \quad \cos\,20^\circ</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_wx9rwtdj">
                                <p xml:id="auto_3nuu4qbj">
                                    <m>\sin\,80^\circ \quad \cos\,90^\circ</m>
                                </p>
                                
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                    
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_m42msksx">
                    <p xml:id="auto_2jiqi7gn">
                        What do you notice on the results obtained in "1"?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_wbmwftqf">
                    <p xml:id="auto_3ia3uem1">
                        Discuss your work with other learners in your class.
                    </p>
                </li>
                
            </ol>
        </p>
        
    </activity>
    <exploration>
        <title>Relationship of Complementary Ratios</title>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                In <alert>a right triangle</alert>, the <alert>two acute angles</alert> are always complementary. But how are the trigonometric ratios of one angle related to those of its complement?
            </p>
            <p>
                Explore the interactive below and investigate your ideas by following 
                <xref ref="inst-complementary" text="custom">the guiding questions</xref>.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <figure xml:id="fig-complementary-angles-interactive">
            <caption>Interactive Activity: Sines and Cosines of Complementary Angles</caption>
            <interactive xml:id="interactive-complementary" platform="jsxgraph" width="95%" aspect="4:3" source="jsxgraph/sines-and-cosines-of-complementary-angles.js">
                <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-complementary" surface="jsxboard" aspect="4:3"/>
                <instructions xml:id="inst-complementary">
                    <p>
                        In a right-angled triangle, the two acute angles always sum to <m>90^\circ</m>. Use the slider to change the angle <m>\theta</m> and observe the results:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <alert>Observe the Angles:</alert> As you increase <m>\theta</m> (the blue angle), what happens to the size of its complement, <m>\phi</m> (the green angle)? What is their sum at any given point?
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <alert>Track the Sides:</alert> Look at the side <m>BC</m>. Relative to the blue angle (<m>\theta</m>), is this the "Opposite" or "Adjacent" side? Now, look at it relative to the green angle (<m>\phi</m>). What role does it play there?
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <alert>Compare the Ratios:</alert> Compare the value of <m>\sin(\theta)</m> in the left column to <m>\cos(\phi)</m> in the right column. Why do you think these two different trigonometric functions result in the exact same decimal value?
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <alert>Find the Crossing Point:</alert> Move the slider until <m>\theta</m> is exactly <m>45^\circ</m>. What do you notice about all four ratios (Sine and Cosine for both angles) at this specific position?
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </instructions>
            </interactive>
        </figure>
    </exploration>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction / Explain</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Key Teaching Points:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Emphasise the solving strategy: when <m>\sin A = \cos B</m>, then <m>A + B = 90^\circ</m>. Similarly when <m>\cos A = \sin B</m>, then <m>A + B = 90^\circ</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Highlight that the term <q>cosine</q> literally means <q>complement's sine</q> — it is the sine of the complementary angle.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Common Misconception:</alert> Students may confuse the identity direction. Reinforce: <m>\sin(90^\circ - \theta) = \cos \theta</m>, NOT <m>\sin \theta</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <insight>
        <p xml:id="auto_e1yfr4h4">
            <m>\textbf{Complementary angles}</m> are two angles whose sum is <m>90^\circ</m> (or <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>radians). 
            The sine and cosine functions of complementary angles have a special relationship:
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_hrohucu8">
            <md>
                <mrow> \sin(90^\circ-\theta)=\amp cos \, \theta </mrow>

                <mrow> \cos(90^\circ-\theta)=\amp  \sin\, \theta</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_lp0vi24l">
            For example, if <m>y</m> is one angle and <m>x</m> is the other angle, then:
        </p>
        
        <p xml:id="auto_sbuhhavb">
            <md>
                <mrow>y+x =\amp 90^\circ </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_nyaznwzt">
            Generally,For any two complementary angles <m>x </m> and <m>y</m>, the following relationships hold:
        </p>

        <p xml:id="auto_sg7ep54h">
            <m>\sin\,x=\cos\,y</m> and <m>\cos\,x=\sin\,y</m>.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_lqmas2x2">
            This means that the sine of one angle is equal to the cosine of the other and vice versa.
        </p>
    </insight>


    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            Learners work through the worked examples. Encourage them to always check that the two angles sum to <m>90^\circ</m> before applying the complementary identity.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_vz44rggq">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_28r9q1nb">
                Find acute angles <m>\theta</m> and <m>\beta</m> if:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_svtmw4mn">
                <ol xml:id="auto_pjc0cu7p" marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_ien198uj">
                        <p xml:id="auto_9wmahv31">
                            <m>\cos\,45^\circ=\sin\,\alpha</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_s5mbv7jz">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ifr0snif">
                            <m>\cos\,\beta=\sin\,5\beta</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_5p3h75jn">
                        <p xml:id="auto_t5wuljx1">
                            <m>\sin\,2\alpha=\cos\,30^\circ</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_h35wg4bz">
                <ol xml:id="auto_deo2fhjk" marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_kxubum1t">
                        <p xml:id="auto_nhxgkwmp">
                            <m>\cos\,45^\circ=\sin\,\alpha</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_oj35aate">
                            Implies that, <md>
                                <mrow> 45^\circ+\alpha=\amp 90^\circ </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp  90^\circ -45^\circ</mrow>
                                 <mrow> =\amp 45^\circ </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_y8miliar">
                        <p xml:id="auto_d3qv08rz">
                            <m>\cos\,\beta=\sin\,5\beta</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_vtto5fel">
                            Implies that, <md>
                                <mrow> \beta+5\beta=\amp 90^\circ </mrow>
                                <mrow> 6\beta=\amp 90^\circ </mrow>
                                <mrow> \beta=\amp\frac{90^\circ}{6} </mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp 15^\circ </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_lkgphtiz">
                        <p xml:id="auto_youeg6oi">
                            <m>\sin\,2\alpha=\cos\,30^\circ</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_k1ax09nk">
                            Implies that, <md>
                                <mrow> 2\alpha+30^\circ=\amp 90^\circ </mrow>
                                <mrow> 2\alpha=\amp 90^\circ-30^\circ </mrow>
                                <mrow> \alpha=\amp \frac{60^\circ}{2} </mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp 30^\circ </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
        
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_yd6325d5">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_x9mat3s5">
                <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are complementary angles.If <m>A=\frac{1}{2}B</m>, find:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_tu61o2wx">
                <ol xml:id="auto_vo5imbre" marker="(A)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_bxx4mmdf">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ec4lbu2s">
                            <m>\sin\,A</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_38m7sj1a">
                        <p xml:id="auto_7bl20cft">
                            <m>\cos\,A</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_y1tqzsc0">
                When we say <m>A \,\text{and} \,B</m> are complementary it implies that, <m>A+B=90^\circ</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_pkuc1qr3">
                Also we have, <m>A=\frac{1}{2}B</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_w5vr2wcv">
                First, Write <m>A</m> interms of  <m>A</m> that is,
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_if9b1usm">
                <md>
                    <mrow>A= \amp \frac{1}{2}B</mrow>
                    <mrow>B= \amp 2A </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_p2hhgzrs">
                Since, <m>A+B=90^\circ</m>, subtitute <m>B=2A</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_feidgf8s">
                <md>
                    <mrow> A+2A=\amp  90^\circ</mrow>
                    <mrow> 3A=\amp  90^\circ</mrow>
                    <mrow>A= \amp \frac{90^\circ}{3}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 30^\circ </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_7t3txpxh">
                Therefore,
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_kpj302k3">
                <ol xml:id="auto_25o1o27g" marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_z03bvoc8">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ycvcakjl">
                            <md>
                                <mrow>sin\,A=\amp sin\,30^\circ </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_d8gartyi">
                            By exact valuyes, <m>\sin\,30^\circ = \frac{1}{2}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_lxw6qi0c">
                        <p xml:id="auto_vb2iqph3">
                            <md>
                                <mrow>cos\,A=\amp cos\,30^\circ </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_724jrjme">
                            By exact values, <m>\cos\,30^\circ = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

        </solution>
    </example>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment / Evaluate (Exit Ticket)</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Objective:</alert> To formatively assess individual learner understanding of complementary angle identities.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Learning Experience:</alert> Learners independently complete the exercises below.
        </p>
    </axiom>

